[start section id="20103"]

I have been asked by Dr. Muse' service to visit with Mrs. Sturges for postoperative education purposes.  Briefly, Mrs. Sturges is a very pleasant 72 year-old female from Arlington, Lake Oswego.
1.  March 2010 - Presented with a six-month history of bright-red blood per rectum.
2.  March 29, 2010 - Colonoscopy performed identifying a rectal mass.  Biopsies confirmed adenocarcinoma.  Multiple hyperplastic polyps also identified.
3.  April 5, 2010 - CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis negative for distant metastasis.  Cavernous hemangioma noted.  Chest x-ray negative.  CEA 1.7.
4.  April 15, 2010 - Endorectal ultrasound performed identifying a T2/early T3, N0 rectal adenocarcinoma.
5.  April 23, 2010 - Taken by Dr. Muse for laparoscopic low-anterior resection.  Per operative note, no evidence of distant metastasis.  Surgical pathology identifying grade 3 (of 4) 4.5 x 3.4 x 1.6-cm rectal mass invading through the muscularis propria involving one of 21 lymph nodes.  15 hyperplastic polyps also identified.  Negative surgical margins staged at T3, N1, M0.
Mrs. Sturges is continuing to recover from surgery and is currently up sitting in bed during our consultation today.

[end section id="20103"]

